positive&#3; impacts&#3; on&#3; rural&#3; access&#3; and&#3; student&#3; persistence&#3; (Jimenez&#3; and&#3; Sawada&#3; 2003).&#3; Parkerâ€™s&#3; (2005)&#3; impact&#3;
evaluation&#3; of&#3; Nicaraguaâ€™s&#3; autonomous&#3; schools&#3; finds&#3; mixed&#3; results&#3; of&#3; the&#3; local&#3; autonomy&#3; effect&#3; on&#3; student&#3; math&#3;
achievement.&#3; In&#3; Mexicoâ€™s&#3; AGE&#3; (Apoyo&#3; a&#3; la&#3; GestiÃ³n&#3; Escolar)&#3; school&#3; program,&#3; increased&#3; local&#3; decisionÍ²making&#3;
decreased&#3; grade&#3; repetition&#3; and&#3; grade&#3; failure&#3; by&#3; 4&#3; to&#3; 5&#3; percent&#3; (Gertler,&#3; Patrinos,&#3; and&#3; RubioÍ²Codina&#3; 2012).&#3; This&#3;
study&#3; found&#3; no&#3; impact&#3; of&#3; curricular&#3; or&#3; pedagogical&#3; choices&#3; on&#3; student&#3; achievement.&#3; Filmer&#3; and&#3; Eskeland&#3; (2002)&#3;
find&#3;the&#3;interaction&#3;of&#3;school&#3;autonomy&#3;and&#3;parental&#3;involvement&#3;in&#3;schools&#3;in&#3;Argentina&#3;to&#3;be&#3;positively&#3;associated&#3;
with&#3; sixthÍ²&#3; and&#3; seventhÍ²grade&#3; math&#3; test&#3; scores;&#3; the&#3; effects&#3; are&#3; stronger&#3; among&#3; poorer&#3; schools&#3; and&#3; as&#3; strong&#3; for&#3;
