opportunities&#3;sometimes&#3;requires&#3;redistributive&#3;action.&#3;The&#3;government&#3;can&#3;remove&#3;barriers&#3;to&#3;school&#3;access,&#3;such&#3;
as&#3; tuition&#3; fees,&#3; additional&#3; parental&#3; contributions,&#3; and&#3; consideration&#3; of&#3; student&#3; academic&#3; performance&#3; in&#3;
admissions.&#3; Such&#3; targeted&#3; actions&#3; can&#3; open&#3; up&#3; the&#3; private&#3; sector&#3; to&#3; marginalized&#3; groups.&#3; These&#3; meansÍ²tested&#3;
approaches&#3;are&#3;critical&#3;if&#3;the&#3;nonÍ²state&#3; sector&#3;is&#3;to&#3;reduce&#3;inequality&#3;in&#3;educational&#3;access&#3;rather&#3;than&#3;exacerbate&#3;
